<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-082-544  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 082 544.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  Feb 1989 v29 n2 p39(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Criteria for evaluating interactive instructional materials foradult self-directed learners.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>DeJoy, Judith K.; Mills, Helen H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Personal Adult Learning Lab at the Georgia Center forContinuing Education, at the University of Georgia, Athens, hasestablished evaluation criteria for adult-level self-instructionalmaterials, using computer-assisted instruction and interactivevideo instruction as the basis.andP;  In the course of the research, itwas found that adult learners want control over the materials theyuse, they impose their own learning styles and requireopportunities to move through the materials in a non-linearfashion.andP;  Many adults also feel threatened by computers until theyget hands-on experience.andP;  Changes in self-concept, dependence onexperience, developmental life changes requiring new learning, andinterest in what is immediately applicable are also adult-specificcharacteristics which should be considered when designingself-instructional materials for adults.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Continuing EducationComputer-Assisted InstructionInstructional DesignCriteriaInteractive Video.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>